snippet.textDisplay: The name BMW used to be associated with high-quality products that lasted a lifetime (My 1978 BMW 528i was a perfect example of this.  Drove it for 21 years and put over 400k miles on it).  The BMW brand is now associated with poorly made, low quality, disposable cars that aren't worth the price (my 2001 BMW 750iL, for example.  It started falling apart well before 70k miles.  Sold it at a huge loss with 78k miles on it because I got tired of repeatedly pouring thousands of dollars into it for repairs every few months).  Net-net: Today's BMW's are about as reliable as a used Yugo.  Never again.

snippet.textDisplay: I currently own 3 BMWs and have had only BMWs for the past 20 years.  The “Ultimate DRIVING Machine” has been replaced with the “Comfortable driving Machine”...soft suspension, floating drive, boring road feedback, while the cost to get into one dramatically increased.  Plus there is nothing intelligent or interesting about the electronics in the vehicle.  Minus the full warranty and included maintenance that used to be standard, it’s simply not a great “value” for the high end consumer that can afford its competitors.  As I am contemplating replacing my older BMW, I am no longer thinking BMW...Such a shame really....

snippet.textDisplay: If you want to know what’s wrong with BMW, it can be easily seen in modern M cars. There is a lack of focus. The M cars aren’t well engineered. Their handling is destroyed by all the weight and lack of a decent shock absorber. The cars are also way too big, a new 3-series is as big as the previous 5-series. In my opinion, which is one that I have created over a long time of tracking and racing BMWs, the last good BMWs were those of the early 2000s. The M cars were focused on being the best driving car, and the normal cars were just normal and could be fun to drive. There is nothing wrong with making every car feel sporty. Porsche has been doing this for years with vehicles like the Cayenne, which is an absolute ball of joy and childish fun, especially the Cayenne Turbo. As for luxury, BMW is far behind the competition in interior quality. BMW uses way too much exposed plastic and things just seem out of place. If BMW wants to come back they need to go back to what they were doing on the late 1990s. Make the M cars properly focused cars, and the normal cars fun to drive but very practical. Also they need to really focus on developing their chassis’s and performance line. The E36 is the best chassis BMW ever made because they put so much effort into it and it shows. An E36 M3 is as fast as a Porsche 993 Carrera. Also ditch all the extra models, stop calling the coupe 3-series the 4-series, it’s a damn 3-series coupe.
